## 7b. Caller-Side Timezone Wiring — `_parse_time()` (P1 Fix)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> I46: `_parse_time()` returns a naive `time`. Callers MUST localize before UTC conversion.
> Without this, reminders fire at the naive time interpreted as UTC — a **silent misfire**.

```python
# In reminder generation loop (notification_service.py or schedule_service.py):
from zoneinfo import ZoneInfo
from datetime import datetime, timezone

naive_t = _parse_time(rule.scheduled_start)
user_tz = ZoneInfo(user.timezone)  # e.g., "America/New_York"

# DST-SAFE: Use fold=0 to prefer the first occurrence of ambiguous times
# during DST fall-back (e.g., 2024-11-03 01:30 America/New_York occurs twice).
# fold=0 selects the EDT interpretation (before clocks change).
# fold=1 would select EST. Product decision: prefer earlier firing.
local_dt = datetime.combine(target_date, naive_t, tzinfo=user_tz)
local_dt = local_dt.replace(fold=0)  # Explicit: first occurrence
fire_at_utc = local_dt.astimezone(timezone.utc)

# fire_at_utc is now the correct UTC instant for scheduling.
# Example: scheduled_start="09:00", user_tz="America/New_York" (UTC-4)
#   → local_dt = 2026-04-29 09:00 EDT
#   → fire_at_utc = 2026-04-29 13:00 UTC  ✅
#
# DST edge case: scheduled_start="01:30", date=2024-11-03 (fall-back)
#   → fold=0: 01:30 EDT (UTC-4) → fire_at_utc = 05:30 UTC
#   → fold=1: 01:30 EST (UTC-5) → fire_at_utc = 06:30 UTC
#   → We choose fold=0 (fire earlier, not later)
```

